Churches, mosques, temples and other recognised places of worship will be required to ensure worshippers keep distance. Only 50 or less people will be allowed to attend worship depending on the size of the worship place. All worshippers will be required to wear masks and sanitise. President Ramaphosa acknowledged the roles religious leaders play in the community, including counselling and prayers. He said the pandemic had taken a toll on the religious well-being of many people hence the need to reopen places of worship as the country moves to level three of easing lockdown restrictions. The President announced a national prayer day to be held on Â May 31. Places of worship closed in March when the country went into lockdown. Some religious leaders have been streaming worship services online. South Africa has so far recorded 24,264 cases of coronavirus. --BBC--